03961nam a22006255i 9780231552417DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20212020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020012371  a97802315524177 a10.7312/llam197912doi  a(DE-B1597)566364  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL2687.Z4395bE5 2020 7aLIT0080102bisacsh00aTop Graduate Zhang Xie :bThe Earliest Extant Chinese Southern Play. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTranslations from the Asian Classics00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tTop Graduate Zhang Xie -- tAppendix I. Dramatis Personae -- tAppendix II. Synopsis of Acts -- tAppendix III. Roles in Acts -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tTRANSLATIONS FROM THE ASIAN CLASSICS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTop Graduate Zhang Xie is the first extant play in the Chinese southern dramatic tradition and a milestone in the history of Chinese literature. Dating from the early fifteenth century, but possibly composed earlier, it is the work of a writing club called the Nine Mountain Society.The play relates the story of a talented scholar who sets off for the capital to take the imperial exams. On the road, he is robbed and beaten by a bandit. In a nearby village temple he meets an orphaned girl who nurses him back to health and whom he marries. Once he takes first place in the exams, however, he comes to regret the marriage, setting in motion a series of decisions with disastrous consequences for both of them.Underlying this story of love, ambition, and betrayal are tensions created by the expectations that family, society, and state placed on the scholar. The examination system offered families the promise of social and economic advancement through an official position. The state relied on these men for the administration of the empire, and society expected that education in the classics would produce moral men. The play offers a critique of the scholar’s ideal, the education system, and the ethical values this process was intended to instill.This first full English-language translation of Top Graduate Zhang Xie features a detailed introduction that discusses the foundations of Chinese drama and the play’s composition and performance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh1 aLlamas, Regina S.1 aLlamas, Regina S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311071097740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/llam1979140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231552417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231552417.jpg  a978-3-11-071097-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK